DEPRECATED: This KM has been deprecated and may be removed without prior notice in future ODI versions.
COMPONENT NAME: JKM Oracle 11g Consistent (Streams) AUTHOR: Oracle
DESCRIPTION - This JKM provides consistent journalizing procedures for Oracle tables. - This KM uses Oracle Streams to capture data changes on the source tables. - When starting the journal on a model, journals are automatically dropped from tables no longer in the set and new tables in the set are journalized. - If the table is already journalized with another model, its current journal data is lost and the table is transferred to the new CDC set. - When migrating Journalization on the model from another KM to this one, always stop the journal with the previous KM and restart with this one. - This KM provides transactional consistency. This means that when using this JKM, you do not have to define the order of the tables in the "Journalizing tables" tab of the Model Window.
REQUIREMENTS System Privileges - The work schema must be granted the SELECT ANY TABLE privilege and the RESOURCE role. - The connection user must be granted the DBA role and be a Streams Administrator
Database set-up - The database must run using the ARCHIVELOG mode. Please carefully review Oracle documentation on this topic before turning this option on, to correctly manage the archives and avoid common issues. For example, if the archive files are not removed regularly from the archive repository, the Oracle instance will hang. - The database or the tablespace of each source tables must be configured with the force logging option. - Oracle Streams must be installed on the Database - When using the AUTO_CONFIGURATION option, the database must run using a SPFILE - The AQ_TM_PROCESSES parameter must be either left to the default value, or set to a value different from 0 and 10 - The COMPATIBLE parameter should be set to 10.1 or higher. - The UNDO_RETENTION parameter must be set to 3600 at least.
- When creating a new Streams Object Group, the STREAMS_POOL_SIZE parameter must be increased by 100MB for Standalone configuration, 236MB for Low-Activity and 548MB for High-Activity. If the MEMORY_TARGET is set to a non-zero value, the database will tune the memory itself. This includes the STREAMS_POOL_SIZE parameter. In that case, there is no need to increase STREAMS_POOL_SIZE. The Database will do it automatically.
Journalized tables - For each journalized table, all the columns of the primary key defined in the ODI model must be part of a SUPPLEMENTAL LOG GROUP configured to log always.
Note: When using the AUTO_CONFIGURATION option, all the requirements are checked and set-up automatically.
BASIC CONFIGURATION 1. Connect SYS as SYSDBA with SQL*Plus and run the following statements -- Replace "SAS" with the name of your user -- This user is specified in the Data Server definition grant dba to SAS; BEGIN DBMS_STREAMS_AUTH.GRANT_ADMIN_PRIVILEGE( grantee => 'SAS', grant_privileges => true); END; / SHUTDOWN IMMEDIATE; STARTUP MOUNT; ALTER DATABASE ARCHIVELOG; ALTER DATABASE OPEN;
2. Exit from SQL*Plus 3. Select the JKM on the model you want to journalize 4. Add the Datastores to the CDC Set (with this JKM, it is not mandatory to define an order for the datastores in the CDC Set) 5. Make sure that the AUTO_CONFIGURATION and VALIDATE options are set to Yes 6. Start the Journal on the Model 7. Create a Subscriber on the Model
OPTIONS (Refer to Option descriptions for more information on each option) VALIDATE: Adds extra steps to validate the usage of the KM AUTO_CONFIGURATION(*): Helps configuring your environment for Oracle Streams CONFIGURATION_TYPE(*): Specify a type of configuration that will automatically tune the different parameters STREAMS_OBJECT_GROUP: Name that identifies the Streams objects that are shared across multiple CDC Set. REMOVE_STREAMS_OBJECT_GROUP(*): Removes Streams processes possibly shared with other Journalized models when stopping the journal JOURNAL_TABLE_OPTION: Storage options for the Journal Tables QUEUE_TABLE_OPTIONS: Storage options for the Journal Tables
LIMITATIONS - When Starting the Journal for the first time, a delay will occur while before the first changes appear in the Journal Table. This is because Oracle Streams scans the archivelog for changes This process might take a few minutes to complete.
- A delay occurs between the availability of the row in the Journal table and the availability of the row for consumption by ODI. This is because Oracle Streams performs some checks to ensure that the source transaction is entirely captured. This process usually takes approximately one minute to complete.
- Only the following datatypes are supported by Oracle Streams: BLOB NCLOB CHAR NUMBER CLOB NVARCHAR2 BINARY_FLOAT RAW BINARY_DOUBLE REAL DATE TIMESTAMP FLOAT TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE INTERVAL DAY TO SECOND TIMESTAMP WITH LOCAL TIME ZONE INTERVAL YEAR TO MONTH LONG LONG RAW VARCHAR NCHAR VARCHAR2 If your table contains another datatype, you should consider using JKM Oracle Consistent instead
- Only the following datatypes are supported on the primary key of the tables: CHAR NVARCHAR2 BINARY_FLOAT RAW BINARY_DOUBLE REAL DATE TIMESTAMP FLOAT TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE INTERVAL DAY TO SECOND TIMESTAMP WITH LOCAL TIME ZONE INTERVAL YEAR TO MONTH VARCHAR NCHAR VARCHAR2 NUMBER
Validate the use of the KM
This option generates an extra validation step during development. Validations performed are: - Check datatypes on the whole Tables - Check datatypes on the Pirmary Keys - Check privileges

This option lets you chose what type of database you are installing the CDC on.
Possible values are: - Standalone - Low Activity - High Activity
Chose "Standalone" for installation on a standalone database such as a development database or on a laptop. Chose "Low Activity" for a database having a low transactionnal activity. Chose "High Activity" if the database is intensively used for transactionnal processing.
The CONFIGURATION_TYPE sets the following parameters Parameter Name Standalone Low-Activity High-Activity ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Capture Parallelism 1 1 1 Capture Checkpoint Retention Time 0.5 0.5 0.5 Apply Parallelism 1 4 16 Apply Disable On Error N N N Apply Disable On Limit N N N Apply Time Limit Infinite 1 Month 1 Week Apply Commit Serialization none none none STREAMS_POOL_SIZE(*) 100MB 236MB 548MB
(*) If Automatic Memory Management is used, then, Oracle Database will tune STREAMS_POOL_SIZE automatically.

This option allows to provide a unique identifier that will be used to generate names of objects that can be shared across multiple CDC Sets journalized with this JKM.
For instance, if CDC is the name of the group, the following naming rules will be used: Capture Process: ODI_CDC_C Queue: ODI_CDC_Q Queue table: ODI_CDC_QT Apply Process: ODI_CDC_A
This parameter must be set using only upper case ASCII characters and must not exceed 15 characters.

Check this option if you want to drop the Streams Capture and Apply processes as well as the Queue when dropping the Journal.
Make sure that no other CDC Sets remain using the same Streams Object Group before checking Yes on this option. Otherwise this will drop their journalization too when dropping the journal on this model.
Use this option to specify storage parameters for the journal tables. Example: TABLESPACE USERS
Use this option to specify storage parameters for the Queue table. Example: TABLESPACE USERS

{

selCmd = """ select count('X') from <%=odiRef.getJrnInfo("CDC_SUBS_TABLE")%> <%=odiRef.getInfo("DEST_TAB_ALIAS_WORD")%> CDC where CDC.CDC_SET_NAME = '<%=odiRef.getObjectName("L" ,odiRef.getJrnInfo( "JRN_COD_MOD" ) , "D")%>' and CDC.CDC_SUBSCRIBER = ? """
# Prepare the statements prepInsStmt = myCon.prepareStatement(insCmd) prepSelStmt = myCon.prepareStatement(selCmd) # Execute for each subscriber for sbs in lstSbs: prepSelStmt.setString(1, sbs) rs = prepSelStmt.executeQuery() rs.next() nbSubs = rs.getInt(1) if (nbSubs == 0): prepInsStmt.setString(1, sbs) nbRows = prepInsStmt.executeUpdate() prepInsStmt.close() prepSelStmt.close() myCon.commit()
